A simple, real-world guide to currying

4 min read
Just now

--

Press enter or click to view image in full size

Have you ever wished you could reuse part of a function instead of passing the same arguments again and again?
That’s exactly where currying quietly shines.
Let’s break it down — slowly, simply, and in a way that makes real-world sense.

What is Currying in JavaScript?
Currying is the process of transforming a function that takes multiple arguments into a series of functions, each taking a single argument.
In simple words 👇
Instead of calling a function like this:
f(a, b, c)You call it like this:
f(a)(b)(c)Each function remembers the values from the previous call using closures. (we’ll understand this clearly in a moment).

If you’d like to explore closures deeply, check out:

A Simple Example
Let’s start with a normal function and then convert it into a curried version.
Normal function
function sum(a, b) {
return a + b;
}sum(2, 3); // 5
Curried version
function curry(fn) {
return function (a) {
return function (b) {
return fn(a, b);
};
};
}const curriedSum = curry(sum);
curriedSum(2)(3); // 5
Here’s what’s happening:

• curry is a higher-order function — it takes a function and returns a new one.

• Each returned function accepts one argument.

• Each function remembers the previous argument via closure.

Why Is Currying Useful in Real Life?
Let’s move beyond math examples.
Imagine you’re building an app where you log messages.
function log(level, message) {
console.log(`[${level}] ${message}`);
}You keep writing:
log("ERROR", "Something broke");
log("ERROR", "Invalid token");
log("ERROR", "API failed");That repetition adds up fast. With currying ✨, it gets cleaner:
function log(level) {
return function (message) {
console.log(`[${level}] ${message}`);
};
}const errorLog = log("ERROR");
const infoLog = log("INFO");
errorLog("Something broke");
errorLog("Invalid token");
infoLog("User logged in");
Now the code feels:

• More natural

• More reusable

• More expressive
That’s the real power of currying.

Partial Application (A Big Win)
Before moving ahead, let’s clarify something important.
Partial application means pre-filling one or more arguments of a function to create a new function, without changing the original function’s structure.
function multiply(a, b) {
return a * b;
}const double = multiply.bind(null, 2);
double(5); // 10
Here, multiply still accepts two arguments — double is just a version with the first one locked in.

Currying vs Partial Application
The difference is subtle but important:

• Currying transforms a function into chained single-argument functions.

• Partial application pre-fills some arguments but keeps the function structure intact.
Both help with reusability — they just approach it differently.

Infinite Currying (Fun but Powerful)
Now let’s look at something interesting.
let infiniteSum = function (a) {
return function (b) {
if (b !== undefined) return infiniteSum(a + b);
return a;
};
};infiniteSum(1)(2)(3)(4)(); // 10
What’s happening behind the scenes?

• Each call accumulates the value.

• We check for undefined so valid values like 0 don’t stop the chain.

• The final empty call () returns the result.

• Closures keep remembering the previous sum.
Notice we check `b !== undefined` rather than just `if (b)` — a truthy check would break on `infiniteSum(0)`, since `0` is falsy but still a valid value to add.
This is currying pushed a bit further — and it works beautifully.

How Closure Makes Currying Possible
Currying works because of closures.
function add(a) {
return function (b) {
return a + b;
};
}add(3)(4); // 7
What’s happening?

• a is remembered even after add() finishes

• This persistent access is called a closure — the inner function retains access to variables from its outer scope even after the outer function has finished executing.
You can even reuse it:
const add3 = add(3);add3(4); // 7
add3(10); // 13
That’s closure in action.

When Should You Use Currying?
Use currying when:

• You repeat the same arguments often

• You want cleaner, more readable code

• You want reusable and composable functions

• You’re working with utilities like logging, validation, formatting, or API helpers
Avoid it when:

• It overcomplicates simple one-off functions

• Your team isn’t familiar with the pattern

• Readability suffers instead of improving

Conclusion
Currying in JavaScript is a powerful way to write flexible, reusable, and expressive functions.
By breaking multi-argument functions into a chain of single-argument ones, you gain:

• Better readability

• Easier reuse

• Cleaner logic

• Stronger composition
Used thoughtfully, currying helps you write code that’s easier to reuse, compose, and reason about.

I hope this article made currying feel less scary and more practical.
